Working with dataframes

We are going to use dataset from Wordbank (http://wordbank.stanford.edu/) for these early tutorials. This dataset tracks boys and girls productive vocabularies through toddlerhood. To make things easier, I have aggregated the dataset across subjects to yield a median vocabulary size by gender and age, with confidence intervals.

vocab <- read.csv('data-vocab.csv')

This dataset is loaded as a dataframe a series of columns. You can see this dataframe now in our Environment window if you are using RStudio.

Each column in a dataframe can be of a unique type.

Lets see what types of columns we have:

summary(vocab)
##        X              age        gender     median           ci.l       
##  Min.   : 1.00   Min.   :16.00   F:15   Min.   : 31.0   Min.   :  8.50

Using assignment, we can overwrite values in a dataframe. For example, lets set the median vocab for 17-month-old females to 1000.

vocab[which(vocab$gender == 'F' & vocab$age == 17), 'median'] <- 1000
vocab[which(vocab$gender == 'F' & vocab$age == 17), ] # now shows 1000
##   age gender median  ci.l ci.h  n
## 3  17      F   1000 31.05   37 35
vocab[which(vocab$gender == 'F' & vocab$age == 17), c('median','ci.h')] <- c(1000,NA)

# reset it now...
vocab[which(vocab$gender == 'F' & vocab$age == 17), c('median','ci.h')] <- c(75,37)

Vectors

R is a vectorized language, meaning that we can perform operations on entire vectors in parallel and not have to operate on each cell one-at-a-time.

Take our vector of medians, for example:

## [12] 182.0 309.0 190.0 379.0 314.0 350.0 270.0 435.0 363.0 471.0 420.0
## [23] 531.5 416.0 513.0 398.5 579.0 444.0 575.0 540.0

Visualization

R includes basic functions for visualizing your data:

plot(medians)

hist(medians)

plot(vocab$age, vocab$median)

but I prefer using ggplot2 which gives us more intuitive options for visualization and greater control over the appearance:

ggplot(vocab, aes(x=age, y=median, color=gender)) +
                          geom_point()

ggplot(vocab, aes(x=age, y=median, color=gender)) +
        geom_pointrange(aes(min=median-ci.l, max=median+ci.h), position=position_dodge(.4)) +
        scale_x_continuous(name="Age (Months)") +
        scale_y_continuous(name="Productive Vocabulary")

ggplot(vocab, aes(x=age, y=median, fill=gender)) +
        geom_bar(stat='identity', position=position_dodge()) +
        geom_errorbar(aes(ymax=median+ci.h, ymin=median-ci.l), position=position_dodge(.9), width=0.25) +
        scale_x_continuous(name="Age (Months)") +
        scale_y_continuous(name="Productive Vocabulary")

Well be using simple ggplots in these tutorials, but the web documentation is great at helping you create publishable figures of any kind.

Statistical tests and models

Finally, R provides a host of functions to run statistical tests and/or fit models to your data.

Lets do a basic correlation just to see how these functions work.

First, get just the female data:

female_vocab <- vocab[which(vocab$gender == 'F'), c('age','median')]
female_vocab 
##    age median
## 1   16   50.5
## 3   17   75.0
## 5   18  121.0
## 7   19  148.0
## 9   20  221.0
## 11  21  213.0
## 13  22  309.0
## 15  23  379.0
## 17  24  350.0
## 19  25  435.0
## 21  26  471.0
## 23  27  531.5
## 25  28  513.0
## 27  29  579.0
## 29  30  575.0

Does age correlate with productive vocabulary?

Plot using basic R plots.

plot(female_vocab$age, female_vocab$median)

# add a line of best fit
abline(lm(female_vocab$median ~ female_vocab$age))

Well get more into the syntax of lm() later, but this function uses a linear model to predict the median vector from the age vector, then feeds this to abline() to plot this line of best fit.

We can do the same thing with ggplot:

ggplot(female_vocab, aes(x=age, y=median)) +
                                  geom_point() +
                                  stat_smooth(method="lm")

What is the Pearsons r for this correlation?

cor(female_vocab$age, female_vocab$median)
## [1] 0.9898423

Is this significant?

cor.test(female_vocab$age, female_vocab$median)
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  female_vocab$age and female_vocab$median
## t = 25.1033, df = 13, p-value = 2.123e-12
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.9688378 0.9967126
## sample estimates:
##       cor 
## 0.9898423

We can access specific variables in this statistical tests output directly:

cor_output <- cor.test(female_vocab$age, female_vocab$median)

When we run statistical models, the vector we return is not only a collection of variables (e.g., from which we can select the p-value, estimate, etc.) but also an object on which we can run various class methods.

class(cor_output)
## [1] "htest"

Here we can see we have an htest (i.e., hypothesis test) object.

This class is limited to the print method.

print(cor_output)
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  female_vocab$age and female_vocab$median
## t = 25.1033, df = 13, p-value = 2.123e-12
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.9688378 0.9967126
## sample estimates:
##       cor 
## 0.9898423

but other classes include other methods like plot, summary, etc.

Lets run another statistical test on some random data. A Welchs t-test:

t.test(rnorm(30,5,5), rnorm(30,10,5))
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  rnorm(30, 5, 5) and rnorm(30, 10, 5)
## t = -2.2653, df = 46, p-value = 0.02825
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -6.4297813 -0.3793599
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  6.350855  9.755425

We can pass specific options to these tests. One common option for t.test is var.equal=T so that we run a standard Student t-test.

t.test(rnorm(30,5,5), rnorm(30,10,5), var.equal=T)
## 
##  Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  rnorm(30, 5, 5) and rnorm(30, 10, 5)
## t = -2.4706, df = 58, p-value = 0.01645
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -5.6801591 -0.5955505
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  6.204019  9.341874

We can also use paired to run a dependent, paired t-test, or use alt to specify whether we want a one-sided or two-sided p-value.

t.test(rnorm(30,5,5), rnorm(30,10,5), paired=T)
## 
##  Paired t-test
## 
## data:  rnorm(30, 5, 5) and rnorm(30, 10, 5)
## t = -2.2317, df = 29, p-value = 0.03352
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -4.883291 -0.212927
## sample estimates:
## mean of the differences 
##               -2.548109
t.test(rnorm(30,5,5), rnorm(30,10,5), alt='less',var.equal=T) # by default: 'two.sided'
## 
##  Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  rnorm(30, 5, 5) and rnorm(30, 10, 5)
## t = -3.6227, df = 58, p-value = 0.0003073
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is less than 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##       -Inf -2.578933
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  5.049028  9.837370

What class is a t.test() object?

class(t.test(rnorm(30,5,5), rnorm(30,10,5), var.equal=T))
## [1] "htest"

Its the same as cor.test(), which is why the output is similar.

write.csv(female_vocab, 'data-vocab-females.csv')
